	<td class="alt1">
	<!-- message, attachments, sig -->
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<span class="time"><strong>Re: New Login Poll... gonna cause another ruckus.</strong></span>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#606B73" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><br />
&quot;John Burton&quot; &lt;john.burton@jbmail.com&gt; wrote in message<br />
news:40c5add8$0$58818$5a6aecb4@news.aaisp.net.uk...<br />
<font color="#7F7FFF"><font color="#7FBF7F"><br />
&gt; &gt; &quot;Should users have a secure method to allow them to transfer ownership<br />
&gt; &gt; of their account to someone else?</font></font><br />
<font color="#7F7FFF"><br />
&gt; I don't mind them asking. Makes sense that they'd want to check that<br />
&gt; it's not just a vocal but small minority who think it's a bad idea.</font><br />
<br />
The problem is, I doubt seriously that they're &quot;just asking&quot;. Imagine the<br />
internal politics around these ideas. Actually putting something in front of<br />
every single player before they log on is not something done lightly, I<br />
suspect there really needs to be a high level champion in favor of any<br />
policy that gets presented in the form of a poll. I doubt they'd risk<br />
generating harmful speculation over ideas that don't have a lot of internal<br />
support. No, I think that if they've come to the point of putting up a poll,<br />
some mighty internal forces are chomping at the bit to implement and this is<br />
just one of the hurdles that needs to be overcome on the way toward<br />
implementation, because someone in a meeting somewhere insisted that it was<br />
a bad idea. The proponents are going to use the poll to show that most<br />
people just don't give a damn, or are ok with the idea, and then they'll<br />
move ahead.<br />
<br />
I continue to believe that the powers that be within SOE have come to the<br />
conclusion that they are leaving money on the table and are going against<br />
the grain of market forces that are generating all of the revenues going<br />
into the pocket of Yantis, et al. These market forces are very real and<br />
people are spending money because there's a need that Yantis is filling, and<br />
this revenue potential has got to be providing great ammunition for those<br />
within SOE who are arguing to monetize it and stop worrying about piddling<br />
details like &quot;game integrity&quot;. There's money to be made, dammit!<br />
<br />
Pure speculation on my part, based on 20 years of exposure to internal<br />
corporate politics within software companies. ;-) It will be fascinating to<br />
watch this play out over the next few months.<br />
--<br />
<br />
Winterfury Thunderwolf<br />
Elder Barbarian Prophet of The Tribunal<br />
Retired Citizen of Firiona Vie<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
</div>
